  <h1>The bearerCORE&#8482; Protocol</h1>

  <p class="lead">
    bearerCORE&#8482; introduces a new class of digital monetary instrument: the
    <strong>CBDC Issuance Bill (CBIB)</strong> — a cryptographically authenticated digital
    banknote issued exclusively by a licensed central bank.
  </p>

  <h2>How It Works</h2>

  <p>
    A CBIB is a PNG image file. Like a physical banknote, it carries denomination, issuer
    identity, serial number, and security features — but embedded in the file itself using
    cryptographic primitives rather than ink and paper. The central bank's Ed25519 private
    key signs every note at the moment of minting. No entity other than the issuing central
    bank can produce a valid note.
  </p>

  <h3>Three-Layer Architecture</h3>

  <ul>
    <li>
      <strong>Issuance Layer (Central Bank):</strong> A hardened desktop minting station
      generates CBIB batches, embeds encrypted metadata, applies cryptographic signatures,
      and delivers packages to commercial banks via secure channel.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Validation Layer (Commercial Banks):</strong> An API-based validation desk
      ingests CBIB files, verifies signatures, checks for duplicates, and registers notes
      in the sovereign ledger. Each note undergoes a full lifecycle audit.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Corridor Layer (Cross-Border Settlement):</strong> FX rate resolution,
      liquidity pool management, and governance enforcement across all 54 AU corridors.
      Transfers settle in under 2 seconds.
    </li>
  </ul>

