  <h2>Financial Inclusion by Design</h2>

  <p>
    Because CBIBs are bearer instruments — value in the file, not in an account — they
    require no bank account, no credit history, and no KYC at the point of receipt.
    A smallholder farmer in rural Uganda can receive a CBIB from a buyer in Nairobi as
    easily as receiving a photograph.
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>No account required:</strong> CBIBs are held in local storage, not custodied by a bank</li>
    <li><strong>Offline capable:</strong> Notes can be stored and transferred without internet connectivity</li>
    <li><strong>Mobile first:</strong> Encrypted QR codes enable verification on any smartphone camera</li>
    <li><strong>Sovereign backed:</strong> Each CBIB is a direct liability of the issuing central bank — not a private stablecoin</li>
  </ul>

