  <h1>Governance &amp; Pilot Programme</h1>

  <h2>Governance Framework</h2>

  <p>
    bearerCORE&#8482; is designed for central bank sovereignty. No private entity controls
    the protocol. Each participating central bank retains full authority over its issuance
    parameters, corridor eligibility, and redemption policies. Cross-corridor governance
    decisions — such as adjusting FX rate oracles or modifying liquidity lock requirements —
    are made through a structured proposal and voting mechanism requiring supermajority
    approval from affected central banks.
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Governance proposals:</strong> Submitted on-chain, timestamped, and immutable</li>
    <li><strong>Voting thresholds:</strong> Configurable per corridor; default 67% supermajority</li>
    <li><strong>Emergency freeze:</strong> Any central bank governor may freeze notes in their jurisdiction unilaterally</li>
    <li><strong>Full audit trail:</strong> Every note lifecycle event — minting, delivery, validation, transfer, redemption — is logged with cryptographic linkage</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Pilot Programme</h2>

  <h3>Phase 1 — Bilateral Corridor Pilot</h3>
  <p>
    Single corridor deployment (Nigeria ↔ Ghana). Central bank minting stations installed.
    Commercial bank validation desks configured. 10,000 CBIB batch minted in Technical Pilot
    mode (specimen grade, not legal tender). Full lifecycle validation completed.
  </p>

  <h3>Phase 2 — Regional Bloc Expansion</h3>
  <p>
    East African Community bloc (Kenya, Uganda, Tanzania, Rwanda). Multi-corridor FX
    resolution activated. Commercial bank API integrations across all participating institutions.
    Retail-grade CBIBs issued for controlled user testing.
  </p>

  <h3>Phase 3 — AU Network Deployment</h3>
  <p>
    Full 54-corridor activation. Production-grade CBIB issuance. Integration with existing
    RTGS and payment switch infrastructure. Legal tender status subject to each central bank's
    legislative framework.
  </p>

